Articles.Content:
I was making a "round the moon and back" prototype mission. Everytime the capsule reenters, unity crashes at around 71-70km height.

I tried updating RP, DeadlyReentry, FAR, but nothing seems to work it.

I can't read the logs, I don't know if it's an install problem or a windows problem. Please I need help with this. But no one seems available.

LOG 1 ; LOG 2

 

KSP 1.10 RO, RP, RSS, Principia.

Definetly is something wrong with Principia. Those DLLs are not loaded properly, whole mod does not work as intended and that alone may or may not be issue for crash. This piece from your log:

I just pointed out some relevant parts from your long log files. I can only speculate real reason of your issues, but my guess is that your GPU is not capable to handle eye candy visual mods. Last error suggest that game  crashed due to general camera handling within unity game engine. And that could be triggered by EVE, scatterer, texture unlimited and other visual improvement mods. First lines of log can tell that you simply may not have enough video memory to handle those mods:

2GB of VRAM may not be enough and can cause CTD on re-entry when additional visual effects need to be shown on screen or something similar. Try to remove those mods and reduce visual settings in game menu to see if that can fix your issue.

You've put mods in the Steam copy of KSP. Not a good idea and a very common reason why things don't work. There's only one thing for it- burn it to the ground and start again.

  1. Copy your save games to the desktop for safe keeping;
  2. Turn off Steam cloud for KSP;
  3. Completely delete all mods, your GameData folder should contain only Squad (and SquadExpansion if you have either/both DLCs installed);
  4. Uninstall KSP entirely, then reinstall it through Steam- make sure you get the right version (1.10.2 I believe), then verify the local files to make sure it installed properly;
  5. Copy KSP entirely (the whole Kerbal Space Program folder out of steam/steamapps/common) and paste it somewhere else, it doesn't matter where really as long as it's outside of Steam's folder tree- just stick it on the desktop if you have to;
  6. Add your mods into this new copy of KSP and not the one controlled by Steam, transfer your save games in and you should be good to go.

It's a bit time-consuming, but cutting Steam out of the loop will only ever be a good thing as it offers no real benefits to have it there and it can cause all sorts of issues like mods going horribly wrong for no apparent reason. Give it a try and see how you get on.
